{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17606867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17606867"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:17:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:17:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15936"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15936"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.08,0.81,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8627"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63254"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8627"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15936"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48705"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7646"},{"type":"tags","id":"8497"},{"type":"tags","id":"8684"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20660"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20665"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63254"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring spermatogenesis, cells undergo a series of divisions and transformations within the seminiferous tubules of the testes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the sequence of cell types during spermatogenesis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary spermatocyte \u2192 spermatogonium \u2192 secondary spermatocyte \u2192 spermatozoon \u2192 spermatid","Primary spermatocyte \u2192 secondary spermatocyte \u2192 spermatogonium \u2192 spermatid \u2192 spermatozoon","Spermatogonium \u2192 secondary spermatocyte \u2192 primary spermatocyte \u2192 spermatid \u2192 spermatozoon","Spermatogonium \u2192 primary spermatocyte \u2192 secondary spermatocyte \u2192 spermatid \u2192 spermatozoon","Spermatogonium \u2192 spermatid \u2192 primary spermatocyte \u2192 secondary spermatocyte \u2192 spermatozoon"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct sequence of cell types during spermatogenesis is: \u003Cstrong\u003Espermatogonium\u003C/strong\u003E \u2192 \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimary spermatocyte\u003C/strong\u003E \u2192 \u003Cstrong\u003Esecondary spermatocyte\u003C/strong\u003E \u2192 \u003Cstrong\u003Espermatid\u003C/strong\u003E \u2192 \u003Cstrong\u003Espermatozoon\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpermatogenesis begins with diploid spermatogonia undergoing mitosis. Some daughter cells then enter meiosis I to become primary spermatocytes. These cells complete meiosis I to form secondary spermatocytes, which quickly undergo meiosis II to produce haploid spermatids. Finally, spermatids undergo differentiation (spermiogenesis) to become mature spermatozoa.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spermatogenesis occurs in seminiferous tubules through mitosis and meiosis, producing haploid spermatozoa from diploid spermatogonia.","The process of spermatogenesis takes approximately 74 days to complete in humans.","Sertoli cells provide structural and nutritional support for developing sperm cells."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015.","heng CY, Mruk DD. The biology of spermatogenesis: the past, present and future. Philos Trans R Soc Lond B Biol Sci. 2010 May 27;365(1546):1459-63."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"item